description.narrative: By end 2021, the government and its partners, including NGOs and communities, provide child protection services in emergency situations that conform to minimum standards, which contributes to Child Protection And Emergencies, Child Protection â€“ General, Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 6: By the end of 2022, women, children and adolescents, especially the most vulnerable, make greater use of quality public protection services (civil registration service, juvenile justice and social assistance).

description.narrative: In 2021, UNICEF in collaboration with government and civil society organizations strengthened services to provide care and support to vulnerable children in humanitarian situations. As a result,23,700 children (12,143 girls and 11,557 boys)against the 26,000 targeted were reached with child protection services, including psychosocial, medical and legal support, food, clothing, family tracing,reunification, and alternative family-based care. UNICEF has also contributed to the Government’s efforts in peacebuilding and social cohesion by supporting the preparation of the National Action Plan for the implementation of United Nations Resolution 1325 on Women, Peace and Security, a process which will continue in 2022. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:02/02/2022
